**Extra descriptions**:

In section [Extension user-defined conditional logical operators](https://github.com/dotnet/csharplang/blob/main/proposals/csharp-14.0/extension-operators.md#extension-user-defined-conditional-logical-operators), it says it should work if both are defined:

* `operator true` and `operator false`
* `operator &` (for `&&`) and `operator |` (for `||`)

However, for built-in types `operator &` and `operator |` cannot correspond to visible API, we cannot reference directly on that, but I personally think this should work because `operator &` and `operator |` do exist.

In addition, even if I defined extension operators `operator &` and `operator |`, it's not working still. It seems that built-in operators are designed as highest priority than all operators defined by users.

```c#
using System;

int i = 123;
int j = 0;
if (i || j)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Either '{nameof(i)}' or '{nameof(j)}' is non-zero.");
}


public static class Extensions
{
    extension(int)
    {
        public static bool operator true(int value) => value != 0;
        public static bool operator false(int value) => value == 0;
        public static int operator &(int left, int right) => left & right;
        public static int operator |(int left, int right) => left | right;
    }
}
```

